use std::collections::HashMap;
use sqlx::{PgPool, QueryBuilder, Postgres};

#[derive(sqlx::FromRow)]
pub struct Customer {
    pub id: i64,
    pub status: String,
    pub city: String,
    pub signup_year: i32,
}

pub async fn find_customers(
    pool: &PgPool,
    filters: &HashMap<String, String>,
) -> Result<Vec<Customer>, sqlx::Error> {
    let mut builder: QueryBuilder<Postgres> =
        QueryBuilder::new("SELECT id, status, city, signup_year FROM customers");

    let mut first = true;
    let mut push_condition = |builder: &mut QueryBuilder<Postgres>, sql: &str| {
        builder.push(if first { " WHERE " } else { " AND " });
        builder.push(sql);
        first = false;
    };

    if let Some(status) = filters.get("status") {
        push_condition(&mut builder, "status = ");
        builder.push_bind(status.clone());
    }

    if let Some(city) = filters.get("city") {
        push_condition(&mut builder, "city = ");
        builder.push_bind(city.clone());
    }

    if let Some(signup_year) = filters.get("signup_year") {
        // signup_year is an integer column; parse so the DB gets a typed value.
        let year: i32 = signup_year
            .parse()
            .map_err(|_| sqlx::Error::Protocol("signup_year must be an integer".into()))?;
        push_condition(&mut builder, "signup_year = ");
        builder.push_bind(year);
    }

    builder.build_query_as::<Customer>().fetch_all(pool).await
}
```

Key points about how this behaves:

- **Only present keys add a `WHERE` condition.** Each `if let Some(...)` checks the map, so absent keys are simply skipped. An empty map produces the bare `SELECT ... FROM customers`, returning every row.
- **Values are bound as parameters** (`push_bind`), not string-concatenated. Only the fixed column-name/operator fragments (`"status = "`, etc.) are ever pushed as literal SQL, and those come from your code, not from the map — so a malicious filter value can't alter the query.
- **`signup_year` is parsed to `i32`** rather than bound as text, matching an integer column and rejecting non-numeric input early.

A couple of things to adjust for your schema:

- Update the `Customer` struct fields and their types to match your actual `customers` table (I guessed `id: i64`, `signup_year: i32`, etc.). The `#[derive(sqlx::FromRow)]` requires the `sqlx` feature for your database and column names matching the struct fields.
- The closure-based `push_condition` captures `first` by mutable reference; if you'd rather avoid the closure, you can inline the `WHERE`/`AND` logic at each block. I kept it in one place so adding a fourth filter later is a single copy-paste without re-deriving the separator logic.

If your filter keys were ever going to be dynamic (not a fixed known set), the important rule is the same one applied here: interpolate column names only from a hardcoded allowlist, never from the map key directly.

